          "body": "The murder itself is narrated in one verse (4:8), but Moses makes it as heavy as possible by the word 'brother' appearing seven times across verses 2-11. The interrogation that follows (4:9-12) is structurally parallel to the interrogation in chapter 3 — God asks where; the guilty party deflects; God pronounces the crime and the curse. Cain's deflection, 'Am I my brother's keeper?' (4:9), has become the Bible's most famous evasion — and the NT will treat it as the antitype of Christian love. John writes directly: 'not as Cain, who was of the evil one and slew his brother' (1 John 3:12). The curse that follows (4:11-12) is precise in its design: Cain the tiller of the ground is cursed from the ground that received his brother's blood; the soil that was his livelihood and identity will refuse him. And the blood itself cries out from the ground (4:10) — the first statement in Scripture that innocent blood has a voice before God, a principle the entire sacrificial system and ultimately the cross will develop. Hebrews 12:24 identifies the blood of Jesus as speaking 'better things' than Abel's — not for vengeance but for pardon."
