          "title": "Seth appointed — worship recovered",
          "body": "Against the seven-generation Cain-line, Moses places two verses (4:25-26) about Seth and his son Enosh. The contrast is deliberate and economical. Eve's naming of Seth ('God has appointed me another offspring in place of Abel,' 4:25) frames him not as a natural replacement but as a divine appointment (*shit*, set, placed) — the same theological vocabulary as God's sovereign acts throughout Genesis. And then the chapter's final verse: 'Then men began to call upon the name of the Lord' (4:26). This is not private prayer — the verb suggests corporate invocation, calling out publicly by name. The Lord's name (YHWH) is the specific object: covenantal address, not generic theism. Calvin and later Reformed interpreters see in this verse the beginning of the institutional church — organized, public, covenantal worship. Whatever one makes of that precise identification, the narrative function is clear: Moses ends the chapter by showing that the alternative to Lamech's boast is not counter-violence but prayer. The same name Lamech invoked for self-glorification (seventy-sevenfold), the Seth-line calls on for salvation. The chapter that opened with the first murder closes with the first recorded corporate cry to God — and that is where Moses intends to leave the reader."
