        "title": "Worship and the heart — why God had no regard for Cain",
        "range": "4:1-5",
        "excerpt": "And the Lord had regard for Abel and for his offering; but for Cain and for his offering He had no regard.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with what appears to be an unjust divine act: two brothers worship; God accepts one and refuses the other. The surface narrative gives no explicit reason, which has generated centuries of interpretation. Three answers have been offered in the history of exegesis, and they are not mutually exclusive.\n\nFirst, **the quality of the offering itself**. Abel brings 'the firstlings of his flock and of their fat portions' — the Hebrew *chelev* (fat portions) and *bekhor* (firstborn) both denote the prime, the choicest. Cain brings 'some fruit of the ground' — the text uses *peri* (fruit) with no qualifying superlative, no 'first' or 'best.' The contrast may be between a worshipper who gives the best and one who gives the adequate.\n\nSecond, **the faith of the offerer**. Hebrews 11:4 is explicit: 'By faith Abel offered to God a better sacrifice than Cain, through which he obtained the testimony that he was righteous.' Faith here is not mere intellectual belief but the whole orientation of trust and obedience that recognizes God's right to the first and best. Cain's offering may have been technically correct and spiritually hollow.\n\nThird, **the absence of blood**. Some interpreters (notably John Owen and later dispensational readers) argue that since Adam and Eve had been clothed in animal skins (3:21), implying a sacrificial provision, the proper offering was blood-based from the beginning. On this reading, Cain's produce offering violated the revealed pattern. The strength of this view is its canonical consistency; its weakness is that the text does not state it explicitly, and minchah-offerings were later legislated by Moses (Leviticus 2) as valid.\n\nThe pastoral point stands regardless of which explanation one weights: **God sees through the offering to the offerer**. Cain's countenance falls not because God is capricious but because he already knows something is wrong — his conscience is responding to a rejection his heart understands. The question the chapter raises at the outset is one every worshipper must answer: Am I bringing the best, or the convenient?\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Minchah* (offering, 4:3-5) is generic — tribute, gift — used in Genesis before the Mosaic system specified it as a grain offering. *Shaah* (regard, look upon, 4:4-5) means to gaze attentively, to turn toward with favor. The contrast is God turning toward Abel's offering and turning away from Cain's — a spatial, relational image before it is a legal one."
