        "excerpt": "If you do not do well, sin is crouching at the door; and its desire is for you, but you must master it.",
        "body": "Verses 6-7 contain what may be the most important two-verse pastoral intervention in the primeval history — and the most ignored. Before Cain has done anything but be angry, God appears and offers him a way out. The structure of verse 7 is a double conditional: if you do well, acceptance; if you do not, something is already waiting. That something is *sin* — the first occurrence of the noun *chattaah* in the Bible.\n\nThe word *crouching* (*rovets*) is the Hebrew word for an animal lying down or in ambush. Genesis 49:9 uses the same word of a lion crouching before the spring. Moses is not speaking abstractly — he pictures sin as a living predator already positioned at the threshold, already waiting for the moment Cain opens the door. The image is visceral and precise: sin does not attack from outside; it waits at the boundary of the will.\n\n*Teshuqah* (desire, 4:7) appears only three times in the Hebrew Bible: Genesis 3:16, Genesis 4:7, and Song of Solomon 7:10. In 3:16 it describes the woman's fallen desire toward the man in the context of the curse. Here it describes sin's desire toward Cain. The deliberate verbal echo is Moses's way of showing that the disruption of chapter 3 has generated a world in which sin functions as the cursed analog of disordered desire — it hunts the person, not merely the opportunity.\n\nYet the command stands: 'you must master it.' The Hebrew *mashal* (to rule, to have dominion over) is the same verb used for human dominion over creation (1:28) and for the sun's rule over the day (1:18). God is not setting an impossible standard; He is invoking Cain's created capacity for governance and turning it inward. The tragedy of what follows in verse 8 is that Cain is the first human being to whom God gave explicit, personal warning before a sin — and the first to ignore it.\n\nJohn Owen's analysis of temptation in *Of Temptation* is the most penetrating application of this verse in the history of exegesis: the crouching posture means the temptation is already positioned, already patient, already calculating. The believer's task is not to fight it after it springs but to refuse the door before it enters.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chattaah* (sin, 4:7) — its first occurrence in the Hebrew Bible. *Rovets* — present participle of *ravats*, to lie down, crouch; used of resting animals (Genesis 29:2) and of the lion of Judah (Genesis 49:9). *Teshuqah* (desire) — also at 3:16 and Song of Songs 7:10; here it personifies sin's aggressive orientation toward its prey. *Mashal* (master/rule) — the vocabulary of dominion from Genesis 1."
